The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 Madurai, Aug. 17: Madras High Court has asked market regulator Sebi, RNRL and Reliance Power to reply to allegations that the merger between the two Anil Ambani group firms caused investors a loss of over Rs 800 crore. A bench of the high court has asked them to submit their replies to a petition that alleged the loss was caused by an arbitrarily fixed share swap ratio for the merger of the two companies.                            
	 New Delhi, Aug. 17: The Centre will meet states tomorrow to resolve all outstanding issues, including rates, on the draft constitution amendment bill for the proposed goods and services tax (GST) where it has already dropped the contentious veto power sought for it on fixing levies.                             
	 New Delhi, Aug. 17: Skoda will introduce a small car in India in early 2012, which will be priced between Rs 3 lakh and Rs 5 lakh. The company will also introduce the Yeti and a stripped-down version of the Fabia in India by the end of this year.                             
	 Mumbai, Aug. 17: Kotak Mahindra Bank has announced an across-the-board upward revision of its lending rates by 0.25 per cent to 16 per cent with immediate effect. The bank has also raised fixed deposit rates.                            
	 New Delhi, Aug. 17: India will have 2.6 million tonnes more sugar stock at 5.8 million tonnes in October against 3.2 million tonnes last year, mainly on the back of higher imports, the Indian Sugar Mills Association said.                             
	 Calcutta, Aug. 17: Dhunseri Petrochem and Tea will set up a new plant to manufacture PET resins with a capacity of 2.10 lakh tonnes with a project outlay of Rs 400 crore.                            
	 London, Aug. 17: Tata-owned steel major Corus will invest 185 million in rebuilding a blast furnace at its Port Talbot steel plant next year.                                                                                                                          
